This is a TypeScript project that runs as a Telegram bot controlling autonomous coding agents.

## Project structure

- `src/` — main source code (TypeScript, ESM)
- `test/` — vitest tests
- `assets/` — bundled files for npm package consumers
- `.claude/agents/` — Claude agent definitions for Docker deployment
- `goose/config.yaml` — reference Goose configuration

## Development commands

- Type check: `npx tsc --noEmit`
- Lint: `npx eslint src/`
- Test: `npx vitest run`
- Build: `npm run build`

## Key conventions

- ESM imports with `.js` extensions (e.g., `import { foo } from "./bar.js"`)
- No `eslint-disable`, `@ts-ignore`, or `@ts-expect-error` comments
- Remove unused variables instead of prefixing with `_`
- Use conventional commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `refactor:`, `docs:`, `test:`, `chore:`
- Stage specific files, never `git add .`

## Dependencies

### Node.js
Dependencies are pre-installed and read-only. Do NOT run `npm install` or `npm ci`.

### Python
Python projects use [uv](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/) for dependency management. UV and a managed Python are pre-installed.

- Use `uv run <script>` to execute Python scripts (auto-resolves `.venv`)
- Use `uv add <package>` to add dependencies (updates `pyproject.toml` + `uv.lock`)
- Use `uv pip install <package>` for ad-hoc installs into `.venv`
- Do not create virtual environments manually — `uv` handles `.venv` automatically
- Do not use bare `pip install` — use `uv pip install` or `uv add`
- If `pyproject.toml` or `requirements.txt` exists, deps are pre-installed during bootstrap

## Environment

- Never read, log, or commit `.env` files or secret values
- Use `.env.example` for reference on expected environment variables
